39:26.694 --> 39:30.860
So, but it is a case of collections complementing.

39:31.862 --> 39:33.744
There is a synergy involved, in other words.

39:33.764 --> 39:35.367
Yes, yes, yes, certainly.

39:35.707 --> 39:42.717
And we've had a number of collectors over the years, particularly faculty collectors, who have consciously collected...

39:43.253 --> 39:47.478
things that they knew we didn't have, knowing that their collection was going to come here someday.

39:47.538 --> 39:51.183
And that it would build and fill in existing collections.

39:56.870 --> 40:02.937
But what do you say to a collector who has this ego thing and wants... It's very delicate.

40:02.997 --> 40:04.198
It's very delicate.

40:04.399 --> 40:09.565
To have it endure as a monument to his or her connoisseurship, you know, and taste.

40:10.203 --> 40:14.227
Delicate is the answer.

40:14.247 --> 40:16.089
Oh, this is a Boccaccio manuscript.

40:16.570 --> 40:17.230
Boccaccio.

40:19.353 --> 40:19.633
Good.

40:19.953 --> 40:20.414
Right.

40:21.074 --> 40:24.057
What catalog is this in?

40:24.458 --> 40:32.546
This is in the catalog that I'm giving you that was for the exhibit that marked the opening of this building in 1970.

40:33.167 --> 40:35.690
And in fact, the cover design comes from this.

40:35.770 --> 40:38.893
Just so I can look for it, because this is magnificent.

40:40.510 --> 40:44.054
This is Boccaccio's genealogy of the pagan gods.

40:49.281 --> 41:00.334
And most of the pictures in here are genealogical charts showing who is related to whom.

41:00.374 --> 41:04.198
When was this book produced?

41:05.901 --> 41:07.142
This is roughly

41:09.046 --> 41:12.991
Roughly contemporary with Boccaccio.

41:14.393 --> 41:18.339
And from whom did this come?

41:20.382 --> 41:20.782
What is this?

41:20.923 --> 41:22.865
I don't remember what the story is on this one.

41:22.885 --> 41:23.186
Oh, here.

41:23.446 --> 41:25.389
Well, it was bought out of general library funds.

41:25.869 --> 41:27.331
When does it say?

41:27.752 --> 41:28.813
It doesn't say here.

41:28.874 --> 41:31.457
I would guess it will say in the catalog.

41:31.497 --> 41:33.921
And if not, I can check for you.

41:33.941 --> 41:34.882
That's OK.

41:35.102 --> 41:36.805
I would guess in the 20s sometime.

41:38.006 --> 41:38.547
Goodbye.

41:38.797 --> 41:46.086
I wonder if they brought it through a dealer or... Oh, look, what's that?

41:46.867 --> 41:47.508
What happened there?

41:47.608 --> 41:48.389
That's a big worm.

41:48.809 --> 41:51.613
I think it's an acid burn of some kind.

41:52.334 --> 41:57.460
Something was spilled on it, and then they cut to repair, because you can see here.

42:00.904 --> 42:01.145
Wow.

42:04.869 --> 42:05.530
Magnificent.

42:12.530 --> 42:17.015
We don't have to go through everything, by the way.

42:17.595 --> 42:19.397
Yeah.

42:19.477 --> 42:20.178
I get the idea.

42:20.218 --> 42:21.079
I think that's fine.

42:21.099 --> 42:32.931
This isn't the kind of library that some of the other libraries that you've visited are, where there's a real emphasis on gathering high spots like this.

42:32.992 --> 42:39.178
I mean, a lot of these have come in coincidentally, and a lot of the effort in building the collection has been in building a research

42:39.952 --> 42:41.654
collection that serves the institution.

42:43.176 --> 42:47.502
That was definitely Bob Rosenthal's philosophy.

42:47.602 --> 42:52.169
Would you say that the collections follow the curriculum, generally?

42:52.529 --> 42:57.896
Or do you have some things that are just wonderful to own that have nothing to do with anything that's taught here?

42:58.056 --> 43:04.105
Yeah, we certainly have things that are wonderful that have nothing to do with what's being taught here now, or maybe was ever taught here, or ever will be taught here.

43:05.106 --> 43:08.811
We have wonderful holdings, for example, of

43:10.765 --> 43:19.953
Dutch emblem books and Dutch drama of the 17th and 18th centuries.

43:20.254 --> 43:22.215
And Dutch hasn't been taught here for 50 years.

43:22.456 --> 43:23.817
But then again, it's research.

43:23.977 --> 43:27.060
It doesn't necessarily have to be taught here.

43:27.480 --> 43:33.446
Yeah, you're sometimes supporting the research of scholars from other institutions rather than your own.

43:33.506 --> 43:34.987
As often as not, perhaps.

43:35.007 --> 43:38.250
I know someone we haven't talked about.

43:38.430 --> 43:40.232
Shaffner, Joseph Shaffner.

43:40.465 --> 43:49.794
S-G-H-A-F-F-N-E-R of Hart Schaffner Marx.

43:50.674 --> 43:51.515
I got the connection.

43:53.957 --> 44:08.751
He collected History of Science, among other things, and gave his History of Science collection here, both books and manuscripts.

44:09.608 --> 44:10.669
Madame Curie.

44:10.949 --> 44:12.010
There's Madame Curie.

44:12.050 --> 44:18.696
Now, without a... Well, you must have some of the Madame Curie things there, I would think.

44:21.338 --> 44:22.579
This would be the place.

44:22.779 --> 44:29.645
Without an inventory, I don't know what to dip into to find what here, except this I can see sticking out.

44:35.931 --> 44:36.672
Oh, look at that.

44:37.873 --> 44:38.333
Well, that's...

44:38.735 --> 44:42.038
It's a Newton Autograph Manuscript, but it's A Count of Charges in the Mint.

44:42.058 --> 44:43.319
That's not very exciting.

44:43.900 --> 44:44.501
Well, it's still.

44:45.582 --> 44:58.934
It's holographic, right?

44:58.954 --> 45:01.577
Newton begins a dictionary of Latin tags.

45:07.022 --> 45:08.083
Look out, look out.

45:10.156 --> 45:10.797
How tight?

45:10.817 --> 45:11.658
Oh, my God, huh?

45:11.718 --> 45:13.761
That's a major manuscript, isn't it?

45:13.781 --> 45:13.942
Yeah.

45:16.926 --> 45:18.468
Does that get you a little nervous to handle that?

45:18.549 --> 45:18.769
Yes.

45:19.871 --> 45:20.652
I'm just going to touch it.

45:21.112 --> 45:22.174
Just a little touch.

45:22.214 --> 45:23.115
What kind of paper is that?

45:23.135 --> 45:24.017
Is that rag, do you think?

45:24.357 --> 45:26.641
Yeah, yeah, it surely would be at that in this period.

45:27.121 --> 45:27.923
Isaac Newton.

45:28.383 --> 45:30.086
And this is Sir Isaac Newton.

45:30.106 --> 45:31.628
Let me just write that down, okay.

45:32.389 --> 45:33.130
What are we looking at?

45:33.691 --> 45:34.172
What is it?

45:35.030 --> 45:39.334
It doesn't look like this is dated.

45:39.735 --> 45:43.418
It's a holograph manuscript written on five folio pages.

45:43.458 --> 45:47.002
Newton begins a dictionary of Latin tags.

45:47.903 --> 45:48.323
Tags.

45:48.984 --> 45:50.265
T-A-G-S, right?

45:50.766 --> 45:54.349
The first entry is abate.

45:56.551 --> 45:57.993
And the last is conduct.

45:58.914 --> 46:03.298
Rarely does Newton give an English version, as in the conduct quotation, but there's a fascinating

46:03.751 --> 46:09.198
aside to the compass quotation, which suggests the compass still used to achieve the correct spacing of the guard.

46:10.139 --> 46:11.681
C-O-M-P-A-S-S, compass.

46:13.684 --> 46:17.709
And that was part of the Portsmouth papers, that manuscript was part of the Portsmouth papers.

46:18.170 --> 46:19.351
You're supposed to be broken up, I guess.

46:19.371 --> 46:21.013
You must have been, yeah.

46:21.033 --> 46:21.454
Too bad.

46:21.494 --> 46:27.522
That's a case where maybe... I think that's fine, Sam.

46:27.822 --> 46:32.408
And he, uh, this came to the university about when, would you say?

46:33.232 --> 46:38.760
Must have been in the... Must have been in the 60s sometime.

46:38.860 --> 46:40.382
I need to check on that for you.

46:40.422 --> 46:41.063
Again, not now.

46:41.083 --> 46:44.629
You don't have to do that today.

46:44.649 --> 46:51.418
Do we... This is a vault.

46:51.438 --> 46:53.381
Does it have a name or is it just a treasure vault?

46:53.542 --> 46:54.483
Just the vault.

46:54.503 --> 46:55.524
And this is the vault.

46:55.825 --> 46:56.145
Right.

46:59.831 --> 47:01.433
Somebody's scabbard is up there.

47:02.611 --> 47:05.375
Yeah, I don't want the stories behind it.

47:06.517 --> 47:10.183
Some of the weirdest things end up in places like this.

47:10.223 --> 47:19.258
There's a whole collection here of Napoleonic stuff.

47:20.780 --> 47:22.944
They've got some Napoleonic stuff at the Newbury, too.

47:23.004 --> 47:24.466
That's stuff, yeah.

47:24.486 --> 47:29.935
Yeah, you know, very memento mori.

47:31.535 --> 47:33.278
That's bizarre.

47:33.779 --> 47:34.040
Yes.

47:34.080 --> 47:39.511
Somewhere in here there's a locket with a lock of his hair in it.

47:39.591 --> 47:40.893
Macaulian's hair.

47:40.973 --> 47:47.907
I'll pass on touching it.

47:52.004 --> 47:58.392
I suspect this was one of those cases where they accepted all this stuff in order to get something else.

47:58.572 --> 47:59.454
That happens everywhere.

47:59.474 --> 48:06.022
In Texas, I have to say, poor Texas does get static for getting things that we're walking by.

48:06.803 --> 48:09.086
This looks like it belongs over at the wing, doesn't it?

48:09.106 --> 48:09.467
Yeah.

48:09.487 --> 48:10.728
I don't know.

48:10.748 --> 48:12.991
I'm not sure what the story is and how we got this.

48:13.832 --> 48:14.894
Unfortunately, it's not used.

48:14.914 --> 48:16.616
Yeah, let's pass on it.

48:16.636 --> 48:18.879
This is Lincoln Pie Safe.

48:18.899 --> 48:19.179
Yes.

48:20.140 --> 48:20.661
From...

48:21.097 --> 48:25.544
Kitchen safe built by Lincoln's father, Thomas Lincoln, and used in his Illinois home.

48:25.824 --> 48:27.507
This came with the garden stuff.

48:28.448 --> 48:29.350
And here it stands.

48:29.550 --> 48:31.473
Here it stands, yes.

48:31.833 --> 48:40.487
I think they got an inquiry a year or so ago from someone who does... Refinishing?

48:40.527 --> 48:41.048
No, no.

48:41.088 --> 48:49.180
Who does these kits, you know, plans for building furniture that are authentic replicas of this or that, and wanted to do this.

48:49.615 --> 48:57.988
Well, if you want to sell them, you can probably... This is an incredible collection.

48:58.188 --> 49:00.271
These are war posters from the First World War.

49:00.291 --> 49:02.835
Lithographs, too, I would say.

49:02.855 --> 49:03.957
Lithographic posters.

49:06.260 --> 49:07.362
I don't like the way that sounds.

49:07.402 --> 49:11.528
It sounds like you're sticking back there.

49:11.548 --> 49:12.569
I'm going to leave that one alone.

49:15.293 --> 49:16.315
Law, not war.

49:17.611 --> 49:22.416
There's a wonderful book published last year in 1984 about World War I posters by Abbeville.

49:22.957 --> 49:23.518
Nice book.

49:24.599 --> 49:27.142
We did a wonderful show of this some years ago.

49:27.162 --> 49:28.463
I bet it was dramatic.

49:32.088 --> 49:41.859
This is really massive.

49:41.959 --> 49:47.365
It has to be massive because the university archives are here as well as the book of Abraham.

49:48.475 --> 49:51.138
Yes, he keeps popping up all over the place.

49:51.939 --> 49:52.700
As well he should.

49:58.107 --> 50:00.530
Someone must have presented this at the University at some point.

50:00.550 --> 50:01.071
It's nice.

50:01.091 --> 50:05.517
It's signed, and we'll have some.

50:05.677 --> 50:07.960
This is a wonderful little collide.

50:08.100 --> 50:09.362
Well, I say little.

50:09.422 --> 50:11.344
It's about 1700, 1800.

50:11.712 --> 50:19.003
volumes, little German almanacs and gift books from late 18th and first half of the 19th century.

50:19.023 --> 50:22.929
That is an example of the kind of thing a university would never go out and collect on its own.

50:23.610 --> 50:25.272
Somebody has to collect that and give it to you.

50:25.453 --> 50:25.673
Right.

50:27.195 --> 50:29.118
Actually, this was bought.

50:29.379 --> 50:29.659
Really?

50:29.920 --> 50:33.425
It came mostly from two different sources.

50:33.585 --> 50:35.027
But you bought it as a collection, though.

50:35.187 --> 50:36.149
Yeah.

50:37.231 --> 50:37.551
Yeah.

50:38.847 --> 50:48.799
And I feel a particular attachment to this collection because we had a volunteer who was in his 90s who finally retired and wanted a project to work on.

50:49.400 --> 50:53.885
And so Bob Rosenthal and I thought, now what can we have this guy work on?

50:53.985 --> 51:03.497
Well, he was a German immigrant from the 30s who loved books and loved art and so on.

51:03.517 --> 51:06.981
And we thought, we'll have him do a checklist

51:07.366 --> 51:23.468
of the of the almanac collection because you know it was catalogued but only as titles so this fellow spent three years coming in every day and going through volume by volume and

51:24.410 --> 51:29.518
looking and seeing, you know, who are the authors that are represented here?

51:30.679 --> 51:33.624
What are the genres that are represented?

51:33.664 --> 51:36.829
You know, are there short stories, are there... Well, he did a wonderful job.

51:37.390 --> 51:38.832
Yeah, and he had a great time doing it.

51:38.952 --> 51:39.733
Remember his name?

51:39.753 --> 51:41.276
Yeah, Bertolt Regensteiner.

51:41.756 --> 51:43.419
Bertolt Regensteiner.

51:43.839 --> 51:46.143
Like the name of the library, but with an E-R on the end of it.

51:47.205 --> 51:49.528
What are the illustrations?

51:49.628 --> 51:51.010
Who are the artists?

51:51.050 --> 51:52.132
Who are the engravers?

51:52.232 --> 51:52.813
And so on.

51:53.283 --> 51:56.789
We still don't have the final product.

51:56.829 --> 52:19.645
We put everything that he did on the computer and are using that to produce indices of artists and authors and editors and so on so that someone who's working on a specific artist or working on a specific author can find out where

52:19.979 --> 52:22.503
where things are in this collection.

52:22.543 --> 52:25.487
What does the collection tell you?

52:25.687 --> 52:31.956
What does the study of this material, what would you use it for?

52:31.976 --> 52:49.260
Well, it's fascinating, for example, from the standpoint of sociology of reading, because this genre was at its heyday in the late 18th, early 19th century, when there was a whole new class of readers in Germany.

52:49.679 --> 52:55.246
particularly women, middle-class women were learning to read.

52:55.326 --> 52:57.709
And so there was a demand for reading material.

52:57.769 --> 53:07.901
And so you have all these things named Minerva and Penelope and Rosa and... That's nice.

53:07.921 --> 53:09.202
We've covered a lot of ground, by the way.

53:10.864 --> 53:14.969
It seems pretty superficial in a way.

53:14.989 --> 53:18.994
There's one more thing I've got to show you because I thought at this time you mentioned...

53:19.733 --> 53:20.875
Phillips, Thomas Phillips.

53:21.275 --> 53:22.257
Oh, yeah.

53:22.277 --> 53:31.971
Because last, a couple years ago, when there were still Phillips things being sold off, um... Trust me, it's not superficial.

53:32.232 --> 53:34.455
It was because I'm writing stories, you know?

53:35.156 --> 53:41.465
This is not, I'm not doing the... This is as big as I've seen, I gotta tell you.

53:41.626 --> 53:49.217
A few years ago, when Krause was selling off Phillips things that he had bought, the fancy stuff wasn't

53:49.906 --> 53:50.987
what we were interested in.

53:52.129 --> 53:57.436
We bought this large collection of Venetian notarial documents.

53:57.476 --> 54:00.620
It's called the Rosenthal collection.

54:02.262 --> 54:17.601
Sam and Marie Louise Rosenthal, who are collectors who live on the North Shore, and who've been very generous to the library over the years, mostly in funds, not in terms of giving things from their collection.

54:19.336 --> 54:21.740
And who are particularly interested in Italian materials.

54:22.300 --> 54:35.280
And so when Bob Rosenthal, no relation, decided to buy this, he went to the director of the library and said, how would it be if we use some of the Rosenthal money for this and then name it after them?

54:35.300 --> 54:35.760
Oh, that's nice.

54:36.061 --> 54:37.363
And this is all Philip's stuff?

54:37.823 --> 54:39.586
This is all Philip's stuff.

54:39.606 --> 54:40.868
That guy was something, wasn't he?

54:41.469 --> 54:43.932
Actually, why don't we, let's, there's no place to look at it.

54:44.053 --> 54:44.874
All right.

54:44.894 --> 54:46.356
I'd love to see some Philip's stuff.

54:49.306 --> 54:57.480
In terms of the three-thirds interest, it's great.

54:57.500 --> 54:58.121
Look at this.

55:01.787 --> 55:08.438
These are documents by Italian notaries, marriage contracts, property transactions, and so on.

55:08.478 --> 55:10.421
Look at the calligraphy, though.

55:10.441 --> 55:15.870
Yeah, well, each notary had his own mark like this.

55:17.167 --> 55:24.199
And so a lot of these documents are related to each other, so you can follow a family through several centuries.

55:26.823 --> 55:30.870
So it's great for historical topics.

55:30.890 --> 55:41.368
It's also just a good thing for young historians to cut their eye teeth on in terms of learning to read scripts of the period and so on.

55:42.023 --> 55:43.244
Very, very useful.

55:43.324 --> 55:44.946
And you probably didn't have to pay a lot of money for it.

55:45.126 --> 55:45.766
No, no.

55:45.786 --> 55:48.509
I don't remember what we paid, but it was quite reasonable.

55:50.851 --> 56:04.664
Bob Rosenthal was so good at how he would orchestrate this kind of thing, because when the boxes came in, he said, now let's open one box, but then let's not open the others.

56:04.844 --> 56:11.490
We're going to bring in Sam and Marie Louise, and we're going to bring in

56:11.639 --> 56:20.680
Jules Kirshner and Eric Cochran from the History Department and a handful of their students, and we'll have a ceremonial opening with a little wine to drink afterwards.

56:21.061 --> 56:28.939
But when we're opening things up, Jules and Eric are immediately going to start

56:29.273 --> 56:34.120
talking about how historically significant this is and how wonderful it is that we've got them.

56:34.140 --> 56:40.169
And he said, Sam and Marie Louise will feel good, as they should, and they'll see a connection.

56:40.489 --> 56:42.372
Sam and Marie Louise Rosenthal.

56:42.652 --> 56:42.893
Right.

56:42.913 --> 56:44.896
Who I interviewed yesterday, by the way.

56:44.916 --> 56:45.316
Did you?

56:45.677 --> 56:45.757
Yes.

56:50.283 --> 56:51.225
I should point that out.

56:55.070 --> 56:57.294
So they gave the money for this?

56:57.374 --> 56:58.335
Yeah.

57:01.167 --> 57:06.655
We talked about what's going to happen to the collection.

57:07.256 --> 57:11.682
I would think that they might have some problems because of having loyalties to more than one institution.

57:11.742 --> 57:12.483
It's a problem.

57:13.345 --> 57:15.147
But I think he wants to be very fair about it.

57:15.608 --> 57:16.930
And you can't ask for more than that.

57:16.950 --> 57:17.170
Yeah.

57:19.834 --> 57:20.755
Yeah, that was nice.

57:20.795 --> 57:27.024
They're a very nice couple.

57:27.265 --> 57:27.525
Yeah.

57:27.545 --> 57:29.588
I'm going to shut the...

57:29.905 --> 57:30.846
You're a winner of the book.

57:31.167 --> 57:33.690
Right, and the freshman... He's collecting the book off.

57:33.710 --> 57:38.577
Right, and the freshman was collecting some science fiction author that I had never heard of before.

57:38.597 --> 57:41.981
That is a twist on it, the senior.

57:43.363 --> 57:45.506
Do I have to write any of this stuff down, or are you going to remember?

57:45.526 --> 57:47.229
I can get it to you.

57:47.249 --> 57:48.390
And you've got my address?

57:48.731 --> 57:49.251
Maybe not.

57:49.271 --> 57:49.912
I don't think so.

57:50.433 --> 57:51.134
Give me that.

57:51.154 --> 57:52.195
I don't have a paragraph.

57:53.016 --> 57:54.258
Chicago mentality.

57:55.280 --> 57:59.305
These self-made men who...

58:01.563 --> 58:08.694
Yeah, they were industrialists or whatever, but, you know, they wanted to make sure that people knew they had a certain eastern polish, too.

58:09.335 --> 58:18.269
Well, you know, it's very interesting, and Paul said this yesterday, there was a feeling here that this was going to be the biggest, most significant city in North America.

58:18.569 --> 58:19.711
Yeah, I think they believed that.

58:19.991 --> 58:28.104
It was doubling in size, and that's what would have knocked me over, the Newbury was its size.

58:28.204 --> 58:29.005
Yeah, yeah.

58:29.187 --> 58:34.216
I'm used to little John Carter Browns, and that's much larger than the Houghton.

58:34.236 --> 58:37.341
Of course, it's not the size of the Widener, but that's a whole other ballgame.

58:37.842 --> 58:40.006
And all these things were happening at the same time.

58:40.066 --> 58:52.748
I mean, the 1890s, you have the Newberry and Carrar bequests, you have the founding of the University of Chicago, you have the founding of the Art Institute, you have the founding of the Chicago Symphony, you have...

58:52.964 --> 58:54.386
This is a way into it, you know.

58:54.546 --> 59:13.091
You have the World's Columbian Exposition, which was, I don't know which way you came from downtown, but straight out from here on the lake is the Museum of Science and Industry, which is in the last surviving building from the World's Columbian Exposition, which was on the lakefront.

59:15.615 --> 59:18.178
Is it true that, I'll just put this on the other side.

